            <div class="Instructions">
                <h3>Instructions</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Grind the mackerel with the cold water, garlic and salt</li>
                    <li>To begin the kneading process</li>
                    <li>Once the texture becomes soft and smooth, put it in a bowl or flat surface and add the tapioca flour then mix it until fully incorporated. There's no need to knead the dough, otherwise it'll become hard when cooked</li>
                    <li>Meanwhile, boil some water in a pot with a little bit of oil. Then start molding the pempek</li>
                    <li>Add some tapioca flour on your hand when you mold the pempek, and make a long cylinder shape for 70gr each and round shape for 100gr each</li>
                    <li>For the cylinder ones or we call it "pempek lenjer", you can immediately put into boiling water. Let it boil until it's floating</li>
                    <li>For the round ones, add an egg inside to make "pempek kapal selam"</li>
                    <li>Making "pempek kapal selam": make a hole with your thumb on top, press it open to create a crater shape, big enough to put an egg yolk inside</li>
                    <li>Add an egg yolk with a little bit of egg white, then close the crater by bringing the corner of the crater together until it's fully closed, to avoid the egg from leaking</li>
                    <li>Then drop it into the boiling water, let it boil until it's floating then add about 20mins more. This additional time requires to ensure the egg on the inside is also well cooked</li>
                    <li>This recipe should make 4 kapal selam and 8 lenjer. It's up to you how you want to shape them, if you think making lenjer is easier, you can also shape them all as lenjer (long cylinder)</li>
                    <li>Once everything is boiled, keep it aside until it's cool down before frying it</li>
                    <li>While waiting, make the sauce for pempek</li>
                    <li>Grind garlic, shallots, dried shrimp (ebi), and chili until they form a paste</li>
                    <li>Place it in a pot along with other ingredients, stir to dissolve the sugar and bring it to a boil</li>
                    <li>Let it boil for approximately 15-20mins, remove from the heat and then strain the sauce to remove the dried shrimp skins. Store it in a bottle or a jar</li>
                    <li>Lastly, fry the pempek before serving, once it's fried cut into bite size and soak with the sauce that we made. You can add sliced cucumber for more taste</li>
                </ol>
